          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p30-b6",
          "parent": "p30-b5",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Write a docstring for the following program. The first line of the docstring should explain, in one short sentence, what the program is. The second line of the docstring should be blank. The third and subsequent lines should include a longer explanation of what the program does. At the end of the docstring, add a line that says \"Author: \" followed by your name.",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p30-b7",
          "parent": "p30-b5",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Access multimedia content (http://openstax.org/books/introduction-python-programming/pages/1-7-comments)",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p30-b8",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 1,
          "text": "1.8 Why Python?",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p30-b9",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Learning objectives",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p30-b10",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "By the end of this section you should be able to",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p30-b11",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "list",
          "ordered": false,
          "items": [
            "Name two historical facts about how Python was first created.",
            "Describe two ways Python is considered a popular language."
          ],
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p30-b12",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Historical background",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p30-b13",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Python has an interesting history. In 1982, Guido van Rossum (https://openstax.org/r/100vanRossum), the creator of Python, started working at CWI (https://openstax.org/r/100CWI), a Dutch national research institute. He joined a team that was designing a new programming language, named ABC, for teaching and prototyping. ABC's simplicity was ideal for beginners, but the language lacked features required to write advanced programs.",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p30-b14",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Several years later, van Rossum joined a different team at CWI working on an operating system. The team needed an easier way to write programs for monitoring computers and analyzing data. Languages common in the 1980's were (and still are) difficult to use for these kinds of programs. van Rossum envisioned a new language that would have a simple syntax, like ABC, but also provide advanced features that professionals would need.",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p30-b15",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "At first, van Rossum started working on this new language as a hobby during his free time. He named the language Python because he was a fan of the British comedy group Monty Python (https://openstax.org/r/100MontyPython). Over the next year, he and his colleagues successfully used Python many times for real work. van Rossum eventually decided to share Python with the broader programming community online. He",
          "dir": "ltr"
        }
      ],
      "book_id": "book_introduction_to_python_programming_1780850976048",
      "dir": "ltr",
      "model": "gemini-3.1-flash-lite",
      "pageHash": "f881c4634748abfb6353d144bacc73e464b49a7b",
      "page_number": 40,
      "status": "structured"
    },
    {
      "_id": "page_book_introduction_to_python_programming_1780850976048_41",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "id": "p31-b1",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "freely shared Python's entire source code so that anyone could write and run Python programs.",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b2",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Python's first release, known as Version 0.9.0, appeared in 1991, about six years after C++ and four years before Java. van Rossum's decisions to make the language simple yet advanced, suitable for everyday tasks, and freely available online contributed to Python's long-term success.",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b3",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "callout",
          "label": "CHECKPOINT",
          "title": "Key decisions",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b4",
          "parent": "p31-b3",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Key decisions; ch 1, video 14 (https://www.openstax.org/r/key-decisions)",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b5",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "callout",
          "label": "CONCEPTS IN PRACTICE",
          "title": "Python history",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b6",
          "parent": "p31-b5",
          "type": "question",
          "prompt": "1. The Python programming language was named after a ____.",
          "options": [
            "British comedy group",
            "Dutch programmer",
            "non-venomous snake"
          ],
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b7",
          "parent": "p31-b5",
          "type": "question",
          "prompt": "2. Which programming language came first?",
          "options": [
            "Java",
            "Python"
          ],
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b8",
          "parent": "p31-b5",
          "type": "question",
          "prompt": "3. Which sentence best describes the beginning of Python?",
          "options": [
            "CWI hired Guido van Rossum to design a new programming language to compete with C++.",
            "Python started out as a hobby and became open source after several years of development.",
            "van Rossum posted Python's source code online after working on the language for one year."
          ],
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b9",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "callout",
          "label": "EXPLORING FURTHER",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b10",
          "parent": "p31-b9",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "For more details about Python's history, see \"A brief history of Python (https://openstax.org/r/100history)\" by Vasilisa Sheromova, and \"History and Philosophy of Python (https://openstax.org/r/100sheromova)\" by Bernd Klein.",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b11",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 1,
          "text": "Popularity of Python",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b12",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Over the years, Python has become a nonprofit organization with a thriving community. Millions of programmers around the world use Python for all kinds of interesting projects. Hundreds of thousands of Python libraries have been released as open source software. The Python community is very active and supportive online, answering questions and sharing code.",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b13",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "One way to see Python's popularity is the TIOBE index (https://openstax.org/r/100TIOBE). TIOBE is a Dutch company that provides products and services for measuring software code quality. Since 2001, TIOBE has tracked the popularity of programming languages and posted the results online. Figure 1.2 shows the TIOBE index over time for five of the most popular languages.",
          "dir": "ltr"
        },
        {
          "id": "p31-b14",
          "parent": "",
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The TIOBE index is based on the number of search engine results for each language. The percentage refers to how many results belong to that language. Python has been among the top 10 languages every year since 2004. In October 2021, Python became the #1 language on the TIOBE index. No other language but C and Java",
          "dir": "ltr"
        }
      ],
